  { question: 'What makes Wellington different from other equine markets?', answer: 'Wellington is the winter equestrian capital of the United States. From January through March, the village hosts the Winter Equestrian Festival (WEF), Adequan Global Dressage Festival (AGDF), and the Palm Beach International Polo grounds — together drawing thousands of horses and riders from around the world. The off-season (April through December) still supports a deep year-round population of high-performance show horses, dressage horses, and polo ponies.' },
  { question: 'What does winter-season boarding look like in Wellington?', answer: 'Winter-season boarding fills months (sometimes years) in advance. Top show barns are booked through trainer relationships. Stalls in WEF-adjacent communities (Saddle Trail, Mallet Hill, Grand Prix Village) command premium rates and often require trainer-network referrals. Pasture board is rare in Wellington proper; most facilities are stall-and-paddock with limited turnout.' },
  { question: 'What about off-season boarding?', answer: 'April through December is the off-season. Rates drop, availability opens up, and some facilities offer summer-only arrangements for horses staying in the area year-round. The polo season runs through April, so polo facilities maintain higher year-round demand.' },
  { question: 'What disciplines are concentrated in Wellington?', answer: 'Hunter/jumper at WEF, dressage at AGDF, polo at International Polo Club Palm Beach. Hunter derbies, Grand Prix jumping, FEI dressage, and high-goal polo. Eventing is rare; trail riding is essentially absent.' }
